Chapter 3: What Do We Share?
Core Question
What values, standards, and practices must be common before we connect?
Understand
Federation requires common ground.
Not identical communities.
Not identical projects.
Not identical leadership styles.
But common enough standards to trust one another.
Shared standards may include:
Mutual aid is organized responsibility
 Trust comes before complexity
 Purpose before operations
 Covenant before money
 Clean ledger as trust document
 Privacy protects people
 Reports are required
 Local societies remain locally accountable
 No extraction of data, culture, hardship, or property information
 Youth are trained, not used symbolically
 Elders are honored with consent and dignity
 Businesses are supported through standards, not favoritism
 Property work requires privacy and qualified guidance
 Conflicts require repair process
 Growth must not erase local story
A federation without shared standards becomes fragile.
A federation with too many rules too early becomes heavy.
Start with minimum shared standards.
Discuss
What must every society agree to?
What differences can remain local?
What should disqualify a society from federation?
What reports should every society produce?
What privacy standards must be nonnegotiable?
What language should we share?
Build: Shared Standards Draft
Minimum standards:






























Local flexibility areas:

Nonnegotiable privacy standards:

Reporting requirements:

Disqualification or pause conditions:

