Chapter 4: What Should Not Be Centralized?
Core Question
What must remain local?
Understand
Federation becomes dangerous when it centralizes the wrong things.
Some things should be shared.
Some things should be coordinated.
Some things should remain local.
The local society should remain the primary unit of trust.
Local societies should usually control:
Member relationships
 Local covenant
 Local meetings
 Local care teams
 Local aid decisions
 Local privacy details
 Local property details
 Local youth records
 Local elder care details
 Local conflict repair
 Local leadership development
 Local story
 Local spending decisions
 Local partnership decisions unless federation-wide
 Local archive
The federation may help with:
Shared templates
 Training
 Regional reporting
 Shared standards
 Technical support
 Cross-society learning
 Federated campaigns
 Emergency coordination
 Business procurement
 Property protection networks
 Youth leadership exchanges
 Regional dashboards
 Conflict support
 Shared back-office tools
The question is:
What strengthens local trust, and what would weaken it?
Discuss
What should stay with the local society?
What could be shared safely?
What should never be visible at the federation level?
What data should be aggregated only?
What decisions should require local consent?
Where could centralization become extraction?
