PART THREE: COORDINATE ACTION

Chapter 9: Regional Buying Campaign
Core Question
Can multiple societies organize demand together?
Understand
One society can support a business.
Several societies can create a stronger route.
A regional buying campaign organizes multiple societies around a business, vendor category, product, or service.
This may include:
Food vendors
 Preparedness supplies
 School supplies
 Repair services
 Cultural products
 Business services
 Youth program vendors
 Local farms
 Bookstores
 Insurance education
 Professional services
 Event support
A regional campaign must have standards.
It should define:
Why this vendor or category?
 Who benefits?
 What societies participate?
 What dates apply?
 How spending is tracked?
 What disclosures are needed?
 How feedback is gathered?
 What report is produced?
 How local businesses are protected from overload?
Regional buying power should not become pressure.
Businesses need organized support, not chaos.
Discuss
What could societies buy together?
Which vendors can handle regional demand?
What standards should vendors meet?
What relationship disclosures are needed?
How do we prevent overload?
How will results be reported?
