Chapter 10: Regional Preparedness Network
Core Question
Can societies prepare together before crisis arrives?
Understand
Preparedness is stronger across societies.
A regional preparedness network can coordinate:
Communication trees
 Elder check-in systems
 Transportation routes
 Supply inventories
 Emergency funds
 Mutual aid response protocols
 Power outage support
 Evacuation planning
 Medical needs privacy standards
 Food and water readiness
 Document backup support
 Youth preparedness teams
 Regional alerts
Preparedness requires privacy and clarity.
Do not expose vulnerable members.
Do not create panic.
Do not promise response capacity that does not exist.
Start with communication, roles, supplies, and local responsibility.
Regional preparedness should strengthen local readiness, not replace it.
Discuss
What emergencies affect multiple societies?
What can we coordinate regionally?
What must remain local?
Who are regional preparedness leads?
What communication route works if digital tools fail?
What privacy rules protect vulnerable people?
