Chapter 12: Youth Leadership Exchange
Core Question
Can young people learn across societies?
Understand
Youth formation becomes stronger when youth see more than one local circle.
A youth leadership exchange allows young people from different societies to learn, practice, report, and build together.
This could include:
Youth facilitation training
 Youth bookkeeping training
 History archive exchange
 Preparedness youth teams
 Business campaign apprenticeships
 Media/documentation team
 Property stewardship education
 Technology project
 Community research
 Regional youth council
 Mentorship circles
Youth exchange must be structured and safe.
Do not use youth as decoration for regional branding.
Give them real learning, real responsibility, real mentors, and real protection.
Discuss
What should youth learn together?
Which societies have youth ready?
What adult mentors are needed?
What safety and privacy rules apply?
What output should youth complete?
How will youth report what they learned?
