PART FOUR: GOVERN THE FEDERATION

Chapter 13: Federation Governance
Core Question
How do societies make shared decisions without domination?
Understand
Federation governance must protect local autonomy and shared responsibility.
If one society dominates, trust weakens.
If decisions are unclear, confusion grows.
If the federation becomes a brand controlled by a few people, local societies may become followers instead of partners.
Federation governance should define:
Who participates
 How societies are represented
 What decisions are shared
 What decisions remain local
 How votes or consensus work
 How funds are approved
 How campaigns are approved
 How conflicts are handled
 How leaders rotate
 How records are kept
 How reports are reviewed
 How societies enter or pause membership
 How mission drift is prevented
The federation should be democratic enough to protect voice and structured enough to act.
Discuss
How should societies be represented?
What decisions require all societies?
What decisions require only participating societies?
How should federation roles rotate?
How do societies join?
How can societies pause or leave?
How are conflicts handled?
